I'm following the article [Globalization and localization in ASP.NET Core -
 DataAnnotations localization](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/fundamentals/localization#dataannotations-localization), but I'm not able to make it running.

What I have is:


**MyStringLocalizer**

    public class MystringLocalizer : IStringLocalizer
    {
        private readonly Dictionary<string, string> _data =
            new Dictionary<string, string>()
            {
                { "Global.Name", "Name Localied" }
            };

        public IEnumerable<LocalizedString> GetAllStrings(bool includeParentCultures)
        {
            return _data.Select(x => new LocalizedString(x.Key, x.Value));
        }

        public IStringLocalizer WithCulture(CultureInfo culture)
        {
            throw new NotImplementedException();
        }

        LocalizedString IStringLocalizer.this[string name] =>
            new LocalizedString(name, _data[name]);

        LocalizedString IStringLocalizer.this[string name, params object[] arguments] =>
            new LocalizedString(name, _data[name]);
    }

**Index (markup)**

    @page
    @using System.Globalization
    @using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.RazorPages
    @using Microsoft.Extensions.Localization
    @model WebApp.Pages.IndexModel
    
    @inject IStringLocalizer Localizer
    
    <div>Global.Name: "@Localizer["Global.Name"]"</div>
    <label asp-for="Model.Name"></label>
    <input asp-for="Model.Name"></input>
    
**Index (code-behind)**

    public class IndexModel : PageModel
    {
        [BindProperty]
        public IndexViewModel Model { get;set; }
    }

    public class IndexViewModel
    {
        [Display(Name = "Global.Name")]
        [Required(ErrorMessage = "Global.Name")]
        public string Name { get; set; }
    }

**Registration at Startup**

    public class Startup
    {
        public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
        {
            services.AddMvc()
                .AddDataAnnotationsLocalization(options => {
                    options.DataAnnotationLocalizerProvider = (type, factory) =>
                        new MyStringLocalizer();
            });;

            services.AddSingleton<IStringLocalizer, MyStringLocalizer>();
        }    
    }

But when I navigate to Index page, the value inside div works fine, but label has just text **Name** and also error message while submitting form is **Name** too.

Is there anything what I've missed?

On ASP.NET Core 2.0, but this also affects older versions. See [this repo](https://github.com/nphmuller/ApiExplorer_IsRequired) for a working repro.

Say I have the following controller action and model:
``` c#
[Route("controller")]
public class MyController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpPost]
    public void MyAction(MyModel model) { }
}

public class MyModel
{
    public int Param1 { get; set; }
}
```

When I check the `ModelMetadata` of the `ApiParameterDescription` from `Param1` the property `IsRequired` is set to true. See the following code which is part of `Startup.cs`:
``` c#
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IHostingEnvironment env)
{
    var apiDescriptionsProvider = app.ApplicationServices.GetRequiredService<IApiDescriptionGroupCollectionProvider>();
    var parameterDescription = apiDescriptionsProvider.ApiDescriptionGroups.Items.Single().Items.Single().ParameterDescriptions.Single();
    var isRequired = parameterDescription.ModelMetadata.IsRequired;
}
```

This is probably because Param1 is a non-nullable and hence always required technically. The reason I think this is confusing however, is because ApiExplorer is used to document the behaviour of your API. 

The IsRequired property suggests that the request should always contain this property, which is not true because if a non-nullable parameter is not included in the (for example json) request, it's simply set to its default value. This means the ModelState.IsValid property always returns true, which means that excluding this property from a request will never result in a BadRequest response.

See for example the discussion over here: https://github.com/domaindrivendev/Swashbuckle.AspNetCore/issues/599

Swashbuckle uses ApiExplorer to create a swagger.json file, which described the API. Because of this confusing behaviour it's more difficult for Swashbuckle to document which parameters are actually required from an API consumer's perspective.

