I have a form inside a Razor page (lets call it MyFirstPage.cshtml). 
On form-submit, the code behind calls and executes action on another controller (UserController.PostRegisterUserAsync) followed by a call to RedirectToPage("/MySecondPage"). 
MySecondPage requires B2C authorization (it has [Authorize] attribute on it).
This correctly causes MySecondPage to load, but it also re-executes UserController (constructor) and UserController.PostRegisterUserAsync. If I remove [Authorize] attribute on MySecondPage, it works ok (there is no second call to UserController.PostRegisterUserAsync)

UserController:

    [Route("api/[controller]")]
    public class UserController : Controller
    {
        public IHostingEnvironment _environment;
        private readonly ILogger _logger;
		
        public UserController(IHostingEnvironment env)
        {
            _logger = new LoggerFactory().CreateLogger<UserController>();
            _environment = env;
        }
		
        [HttpPost("register")]
        public async Task<IActionResult> PostRegisterUserAsync([FromBody]UserObject myUserObject, 
        CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            // process user registration
        }
    }

in Startup.cs:
`services.AddTransient<UserController, UserController>();`


myFirstPage.cshtml.cs:

    public class MyFirstPageModel : PageModel
    {
        private UserController  _userController ;
        private UserObject _user;

        public MyFirstPageModel( UserController userController)
        {
             _userController = userController;
        }

        public async Task<IActionResult> OnPostMethodAsync(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            await _userController.PostRegisterUserAsync(_user, cancellationToken);
            return RedirectToPage("/mySecondPage");
        }
    }


MySecondPage:


    [Authorize]
    public class MySecondPageModel : PageModel
    {
        // code
    }

How to prevent that second (unexpected) call to the UserController, without removing [Authorize] on MySecondPage?

It seems that per default dates in JavaScript format don't bind to DateTime. 

I have an ajax post:
``` JavaScript
$.post({
    url: "@Url.Action("MyAction", "Home")",
    cache: false,
    dataType: "json",
    data: {
        date1: new Date().toString(), date2: new Date(), date3: new Date().toISOString()
    }
}
```

And a view model:
``` CSharp
public class Class1
{
    public DateTime Date1 { get; set; }
    public DateTime Date2 { get; set; }
    public DateTime Date3 { get; set; }
}
```

And an action:
``` CSharp
[HttpPost]        
public IActionResult MyAction([FromForm]Class1 data)
{
    return new JsonResult(null);
}
```

This gets submitted:
```
date1=Mon+Feb+19+2018+20:10:28+GMT+0100
date2=Mon+Feb+19+2018+20:10:28+GMT+0100
date3=2018-02-19T19:10:28.165Z
```

Only `Date3` gets bound. Maybe it would make sense that `Date1` and `Date2` get bound out of the box too?

In my specific use case I wanted to get the data object that jQuery posts from knockout's `ko.mapping.toJS`. I have to do a workaround (e.g. using `data: JSON.parse(ko.mapping.toJSON(...))`) in order to make the dates bind because they are all Date objects and not ISO date strings.

